result.envelope_design_recommendation:
To block Mistral with a synthesized warning that the frontend renders correctly, APF must produce a TWO-STAGE replacement. STAGE 1 (tRPC POST /api/trpc/message.newChat?batch=1 response): Reply with the standard tRPC batch result array [{'result':{'data':{'json':{'id':<fake-msg-id-uuid>,'chatId':<fake-chat-id-uuid>,'role':'user','content':[{'type':'text','text':<original-prompt>}],'createdAt':<iso-ts>,...minimal fields...}}}}] -- frontend uses these IDs for the next call. STAGE 2 (POST /api/chat response): Reply with chunked text body using the numbered-prefix NDJSON protocol: send '16:{"json":{"disclaimers":[]}}
' then ONE OR MORE '15:{"json":{"type":"message","message":{"id":<asst-msg-id>,"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"<WARNING TEXT>"}],...}}}
' followed by '8:null
' to terminate. Headers must include Content-Encoding compatible with what client expects (zstd negotiation may need stripping -- easier to omit zstd and send identity). Critical: every payload object is wrapped in {'json':<body>} (superjson envelope) and opcode '15' carries message chunks while '8:null' signals end. Alternative simpler approach: skip Stage 1 interception and instead inject warning at Stage 2 only by replacing the streamed content with a single full-message chunk + 8:null. Note: NO WebSockets -- pure HTTP, easier to MITM than WS-based services. Same chatId UUID must thread through both stages if Stage 1 is intercepted.

